sec.p:
The overlap coefficient is a similarity measure for the overlap between two sets. For two sets G and H, the overlap coefficient is given by
o G H = | G ∩ H | min { | G | , | H | }
where 0 ≤ oGH ≤ 1. The overlap coefficient is simply the size of the intersection divided by the size of the smaller of the two sets. We chose the overlap coefficient instead of other measures of overlap like the Jaccard index because it highlights whenever a pathway is a fully contained within another pathway. If a set G is a subset of H, the overlap coefficient is always 1. On the other hand, if the sets G and H are disjoint, the overlap coefficient is always 0.
